1 borrow the following note from Mr. Ellis: ‘Bacon doubtless refers to the austerities of the order of Feiiillans. Jean de la Baniere, after holding the Cistercian abbey of Feiiillans in commendam for eleven years, re· nounced the world in 1573, and in the course of a few years introduced amost austere rule of life into the abbey of which he was the head. His monks knelt on the iloor during their refections, and some of them were in the habit of drinking out of skulls. They abstained from egga fish, butter, oil, aud even salt, and confined themselves to pottage made of herbs boiled in water, and breed so coarse and black that beasts refused to eat of it. After a while they gave up wine also. Clement Vlll permitted the society to draw up constitutions for the establishment ol their rule. By these the excessive rigour of their way of life was checked, which was done in obedience to the Pope, and in consequence of the deaths of lourteen mouks in a single week at Feiiillans. These constitutions were ratified iu 1595.
